      "id": "pta-s46",
      "number": "46",
      "text": "46 (1) Subject to subsection (2), if the registrar is satisfied that a licensee has failed to comply with this Act, the regulations or the terms and conditions of the licensee's licence, the registrar may, in accordance with this Part and within one year after becoming aware of the failure to comply, take one or more of the following actions: (a) order that the licensee's licence be suspended for any period the registrar considers necessary; (b) make an order prohibiting the licensee from transferring, amending, replacing, renewing or obtaining a new licence; (c) order the licensee to stop operating or cause others to stop operating motor vehicles under the licence, stop providing services under the licence, cease displaying vehicle identifiers, collect them, and return them to the registrar; (c.1) in relation to a licence that includes a passenger directed vehicle authorization or transportation network services authorization, order the licensee to cause a person to cease displaying a record check certificate, collect it, ensure a person has no access to the licensee's online platform as a driver, or remove a person's record check certificate from the platform; (d) order that the licensee's licence, or an authorization included in that licence, be cancelled; (e) make an order imposing an administrative fine on the licensee. (2) If the registrar proposes to impose a penalty under subsection (1), the registrar must notify the licensee in writing, advising which penalty the registrar intends to impose, the period of any suspension or prohibition, the amount of any proposed administrative fine (which must not exceed $50 000), the reasons, and that the licensee may within 7 days provide a written response. (2.1) Before proposing to impose an administrative fine, the registrar must consider previous enforcement actions, the gravity and magnitude of the failure, the extent of harm or potential harm, whether the failure was repeated or continuous or deliberate, any economic benefit derived, the licensee's efforts to prevent or correct the failure, and prescribed matters. (6) A penalty referred to in subsection (1) (a) or (b) may extend beyond the normal renewal date of the licence but must not exceed a period of 3 years.",
